1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:03,560
Bridges carry cities every day — and when one fails,

2
00:00:03,560 --> 00:00:06,370
the cost is measured in lives, not dollars.

3
00:00:06,370 --> 00:00:10,100
As more of the world's bridges age past their prime,

4
00:00:10,100 --> 00:00:14,960
the hardest question in infrastructure safety is deceptively simple: how do you catch

5
00:00:14,960 --> 00:00:18,690
a structure's quiet, invisible changes before visible damage ever appears?

6
00:00:18,690 --> 00:00:22,970
Traditional monitoring struggles with exactly this — sparse sensors leave blind spots,

7
00:00:22,970 --> 00:00:27,600
and even where fiber-optic sensing gives full coverage, the raw data floods in

8
00:00:27,600 --> 00:00:30,810
faster than any engineer can read it by hand.

9
00:00:30,810 --> 00:00:34,360
This is MurSense: an AI agent that lets anyone ask,

10
00:00:34,360 --> 00:00:38,270
in plain language, how a bridge is doing right now —

11
00:00:38,270 --> 00:00:42,180
and get back an answer grounded in real, validated engineering analysis,

12
00:00:42,180 --> 00:00:43,250
not a guess.

13
00:00:43,250 --> 00:00:48,960
Under the hood, an AI agent reads the question and routes it to

14
00:00:48,960 --> 00:00:53,350
one of three core capabilities — vibration analysis, health diagnosis,

15
00:00:53,350 --> 00:00:58,620
or knowledge Q&A — then hands the actual computation to a validated,

16
00:00:58,620 --> 00:01:03,020
deterministic algorithm engine: power-spectral-density analysis, modal-frequency extraction, five-level alert scoring.

17
00:01:03,020 --> 00:01:08,260
Every number it returns comes from that engine, run on real DAS fiber-optic

18
00:01:08,260 --> 00:01:13,500
sensing data — 100 Hz sampling, 1,034 channels — never invented by the

19
00:01:13,500 --> 00:01:14,300
AI itself.

20
00:01:15,180 --> 00:01:16,130
Let's log in.

21
00:01:16,130 --> 00:01:20,370
This is MurSense's main workspace: a sidebar for conversation history and saved projects,

22
00:01:20,370 --> 00:01:24,620
a top bar for language and theme, and a center panel that starts

23
00:01:24,620 --> 00:01:28,860
every session with one simple question — what would you like to know

24
00:01:28,860 --> 00:01:29,840
about bridge health?

25
00:01:35,180 --> 00:01:38,460
One click switches the whole interface to a dark theme —

26
00:01:38,460 --> 00:01:41,440
same layout, easier on the eyes for a night shift.

27
00:01:42,340 --> 00:01:47,610
The interface itself is fully trilingual — Chinese, English, French —

28
00:01:47,610 --> 00:01:49,530
switching instantly, no reload.

29
00:01:49,530 --> 00:01:52,690
Even the assistant's own name changes with the language.

30
00:01:53,600 --> 00:02:00,230
Expand "More" and you'll see MurSense's full capability set laid out as one-click

31
00:02:00,230 --> 00:02:04,820
examples: vibration analysis, spectral diagnostics, knowledge Q&A, report generation.

32
00:02:04,820 --> 00:02:09,070
There's even a fifth card for load identification — clearly marked as a

33
00:02:09,070 --> 00:02:11,690
planned direction, not something we're claiming works today.

34
00:02:12,590 --> 00:02:17,460
The user guide walks a first-time visitor through exactly how to talk to

35
00:02:17,460 --> 00:02:22,320
the assistant — say a date, say "analyze", say "export a report" —

36
00:02:22,320 --> 00:02:26,810
and shows the real scale of the data underneath: 100 hertz sampling,

37
00:02:26,810 --> 00:02:27,940
1,034 channels, continuously.

38
00:02:28,850 --> 00:02:32,950
At any point you can pick a specific data file from this dropdown

39
00:02:32,950 --> 00:02:35,780
— MurSense fills in the right analysis prompt automatically.

40
00:02:36,850 --> 00:02:38,340
Now the core of the product.

41
00:02:38,340 --> 00:02:41,730
Ask, in plain language, how the bridge is doing today.

42
00:02:41,730 --> 00:02:45,770
Watch the status line — the assistant is routing this to a real

43
00:02:45,770 --> 00:02:47,330
analysis tool, not just chatting.

44
00:02:49,850 --> 00:02:52,490
Moments later: a complete health assessment.

45
00:02:52,490 --> 00:02:56,240
At the top, the exact tool that ran — check_bridge_health —

46
00:02:56,240 --> 00:02:59,990
so you know this came from validated code, not a guess.

47
00:02:59,990 --> 00:03:05,740
Below it, the scalar metrics: strain and modal frequency, both compared against baseline.

48
00:03:05,740 --> 00:03:10,030
And here's the nuance a real system produces that a mockup wouldn't:

49
00:03:10,030 --> 00:03:14,680
the scalar averages look perfectly normal, but the spatial breakdown flags a localized

50
00:03:14,680 --> 00:03:18,970
anomaly — an orange-level warning at a specific stretch of the bridge,

51
00:03:18,970 --> 00:03:20,760
with a clear recommendation attached.

52
00:03:21,850 --> 00:03:26,630
Ask for the power spectrum on a specific channel, and MurSense draws it

53
00:03:26,630 --> 00:03:31,400
live — this is channel 519's real frequency curve, with four modal frequencies

54
00:03:31,400 --> 00:03:33,980
automatically picked out and labeled in hertz.

55
00:03:39,850 --> 00:03:45,290
Zoom back out to the full picture: a waterfall plot across all 1,034

56
00:03:45,290 --> 00:03:49,470
channels, showing exactly where each resonant frequency runs consistently —

57
00:03:49,470 --> 00:03:50,310
or doesn't.

58
00:03:52,850 --> 00:03:56,940
MurSense isn't limited to running numbers — ask it a domain question directly,

59
00:03:56,940 --> 00:04:01,040
like how to read an anomaly in this plot, and it retrieves from

60
00:04:01,040 --> 00:04:05,130
its own knowledge base and walks you through an actual diagnostic decision tree.

61
00:04:10,850 --> 00:04:15,950
Every answer carries the same footer: which model answered, how many tokens it

62
00:04:15,950 --> 00:04:19,860
used, how long it took — and three one-click actions:

63
00:04:19,860 --> 00:04:21,040
copy, export, save.

64
00:04:21,950 --> 00:04:26,690
Export turns any analysis into a formatted Word report in one click —

65
00:04:26,690 --> 00:04:31,070
tables, figures, and all — ready to hand to a bridge owner.

66
00:04:31,990 --> 00:04:36,840
Save archives the same analysis into a named project, so nothing gets lost

67
00:04:36,840 --> 00:04:37,590
between sessions.

68
00:04:41,990 --> 00:04:46,040
That saved report shows up immediately in Projects — title,

69
00:04:46,040 --> 00:04:50,090
word count, figure count, health level, all at a glance.

70
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:54,170
Open any archived report and you get a full editor:

71
00:04:54,170 --> 00:04:57,350
Markdown on the left, a live preview on the right,

72
00:04:57,350 --> 00:05:01,470
and a one-click export to a standalone HTML file you can share with

73
00:05:01,470 --> 00:05:01,970
anyone.

74
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:08,430
The Data Space is where the raw material lives: your own uploaded recordings,

75
00:05:08,430 --> 00:05:12,860
with a live multi-channel waveform preview you can inspect channel by channel —

76
00:05:12,860 --> 00:05:17,290
pick specific channels to compare and adjust their spacing for a clearer view

77
00:05:17,290 --> 00:05:19,330
— before ever running an analysis.

78
00:05:19,330 --> 00:05:24,720
There's also a shared public demo dataset, and an organization-shared tier gated to

79
00:05:24,720 --> 00:05:25,550
enterprise accounts.

80
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:32,110
Click analyze on any file here, and MurSense jumps straight back to the

81
00:05:32,110 --> 00:05:34,630
chat with the right prompt already filled in.

82
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:40,690
The account pages round out the basics: profile, real usage statistics,

83
00:05:40,690 --> 00:05:45,370
a push-notification setup reserved for the cloud-deployed tier, and password management.

84
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:53,700
System settings let you point MurSense at your own LLM provider and API

85
00:05:53,700 --> 00:05:58,390
key, set a preferred reply language, and switch the whole interface's language —

86
00:05:58,390 --> 00:05:59,840
all without restarting anything.

87
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:05,160
And a direct feedback channel, straight to the developer.

88
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:12,310
One rule keeps all of this trustworthy: the AI never writes analysis code

89
00:06:12,310 --> 00:06:16,290
on the fly, and it never sees the raw waveform data directly.

90
00:06:16,290 --> 00:06:21,340
A validated algorithm package does the actual computation; the model only decides which

91
00:06:21,340 --> 00:06:24,060
tool to call and explains the result.

92
00:06:24,060 --> 00:06:29,490
MurSense: real sensors, real analysis, and an assistant that shows its work.
